ACT III. Senm: III.

Pamphilus, having removed all that were about him, is now at liberty to open his mind freely, and let us into the knowledge of what he had seen when he went in to visit Philumena, and which was the cause of that sorrow and dejection, which now appear so manifest in ¹ his looks. Considering the perplexity into which Pamphilus is now thrown, we are not to wonder at the concern he seems to be in. Though he has resolved to abandon his wife, yet it costs him a hard struggle; for when love -has once firmly taken root, it is not easy, ..even upon the greatest provocation, to conquer it.
